<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881013-0053 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief -- General Automation Inc.: Talks Held With WesPac About Business Combination </HL><SO> </SO><CO> GA WNEWS </CO><IN> TNM </IN><TEXT>   General Automation Inc., Anaheim, Calif., said it has begun &quot;business combination&quot; talks with WesPac Technologies Corp. and named an executive affiliated with WesPac as its own president, chief executive officer and board member.    Appointed to the posts was Norris W. Agee, 50 years old, who succeeds Michael J. O'Donnell, who resigned, General Automation said. Mr. O'Donnell, 33, only assumed the posts in August, succeeding Leonard N. Mackenzie, 50, who remains vice chairman.    General Automation, a computer company, which posted a loss for its fiscal year, said WesPac is a profitable maker of computerized transaction-processing systems with annual sales of about $12 million. WesPac is based in Irvine, Calif. For the year ended June 30, General Automation posted a loss of $11 million on sales of $50.9 million.    A General Automation spokesman said the potential business combination could involve a merger, acquisition, joint venture, or other arrangement. He said Mr. Agee is a WesPac consultant and shareholder. </TEXT></DOC>